# ~/Projects/<project>/AGENTS.md — example template

If you add a new top-level project under `~/Projects/`, the project
should ship its own `AGENTS.md` describing its stack and conventions.
This is a starter template; copy and adapt.

```markdown
# <Project name>

<One-line description: what this project is, what it does, who uses it.>

## What this is

<2-3 paragraphs: the problem, the solution, the stack.>

## Dev setup

<How a new dev gets the project running locally. Include the exact
clone + install + setup commands.>

## Run

<How to start the dev server, run a single command, etc.>

## Test

<How to run the test suite. Include the test runner command and any
fixtures that need to be set up first.>

## Deploy

<Where this lives in production, how to push a release, what
infrastructure it depends on.>

## Key files

<Bullet list of the most important files / dirs, with a one-liner
about what each is for.>

## See also

- `~/AGENTS.md` — workspace layout, project index, sovereignty rules.
- `~/.hermes/AGENTS.md` — runtime contract, workflow rules, scratch layout.
- `<link to the project's kanban board, if any>`
- `<link to design docs / RFCs, if any>`

## Things not to do

<Specific anti-patterns, past bugs, known footguns.>
```

Replace the angle-bracketed sections with your project's content. The
**`## See also`** section is critical — every project AGENTS.md must
point back to the two parent contracts so future agents don't have to
guess at workspace-wide rules.
